  <h1>Content Publishing Workflow</h1>

<div class="notes">
  <h3>Important Notes</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      You can upload your assets (images, PDFs, etc.) in the <strong>Site Assets</strong> folder if they are not hosted elsewhere.
      Organize them under a content-type-specific folder, and then inside the content offering folder.<br/>
      <strong>Example:</strong> If your assets belong to <em>Product â†’ Oracle</em>, create and store them under <code>Product/Oracle</code> folder.
    </li>
    <li>
      You can <a href="#">onboard your colleagues</a> as Content Creators to help manage and edit content collaboratively.
    </li>
  </ul>
</div>


  <div class="card-container">

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Step 1: Raise JIRA Request</h2>
      <p>Start by raising a JIRA ticket with content and metadata details using the provided form.</p>
      <a href="#">Raise JIRA Request</a>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Step 2: CMS Setup by Support Team</h2>
      <p>The CMS Support Team will create a blank page and do the initial setup based on JIRA details.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Step 3: Update Page Content</h2>
      <p>After setup, update the content on the blank page according to your requirements.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Step 4: Send for Approval</h2>
      <p>Submit the page for approval. The assigned approver will be automatically notified.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Step 5: Approval & Publishing</h2>
      <p>Once approved, the content will be published to the live environment.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Step 6: First-Time Publication Request (If Applicable)</h2>
      <p>If this is the first time publishing, raise a request to enable/disable visibility on the IT Portal. Otherwise, content will go live within 24 hours.</p>
      <a href="#">Raise Enable/Disable Request</a>
    </div>

  </div>
